Have you ever wondered what you could do with all the empty tea light holders? Make some pretty ornaments. Here’s how you do it. Take your empty tea light tin, remove the metal wick part, and carefully make your straight or angled cuts. Then lay it flat as much as you can. On a piece of card board make holes for the star with a pointed tip and one to hang the ornaments. Or, if you are making them for a garland like I did, make holes, then cut slits and thread some ribbon through and space them apart as you like. I love using these recycled tins with a little gold velvet ribbon to mix into my greenery!

We are down to our last bag of @nutella biscuits from our trip to France— so naturally we made homemade Nutella biscuits! We used our friend Lorna’s short bread recipe: 1 1/2 sticks of salted butter, cubed and softened a little by just letting it sit on the counter, 1/2 cup sugar, 1 teaspoon vanilla & 3 cups flour (sifted). We used round cookie cutters with a smaller heart inside pressed into the top cookie just a little, then we used a stamp to make an n for Nutella. Bake in a 350° oven for 5 minutes, turn pan and bake until lightly browned. Watch closely. Have you tried the one-ingredient chocolate mousse yet? I’ve been meaning to try it forever and since it fits with my “eating better in the new year” now is the perfect time. 

You’ll need a 3.5 ounce bar of the darkest chocolate you can find. And a bit of water. 

Melt the chocolate and water (a scant 2.5 ounces) and remove from the heat and pour into a bowl over a larger bowl of ice. Whisk for a few minutes…I think maybe 3?? When it’s at the consistency that you can still pour. 

Then make sure to have some tiny cups ready and pour into 2 and top with a little sea salt. Refrigerate and enjoy! 

What does it taste like? A dark truffle. #mostlovelythings #oneingredientfoods #oneingredientchocolatemousse #darkchocolate #explore

We made the viral garlic butter candle…it’s interesting. Easy to do and a fun idea! Here’s how we did it. We roasted a head of garlic while the butter was softening. Blended the roasted garlic with the soft butter and whisked it together. Punch a hole in a solo cup and added a wick. Added the soft garlic butter and positioned the wick in the center. We filled 2 cups about half way. Covered and put in the freezer for a couple of hours. Removed the cups and put inside a hollowed out loaf of bread that I cut about the same size as the cups. Lit the butter candles. It takes a good 30 minutes before you can dip (or I prefer to use a butter knife) and easier to avoid blowing out the candle that way! We made the oh so popular spicy salmon sushi cups and it’s definitely going to be in the rotation for a quick lunch or dinner! Here’s what we did: we made sushi rice, added a splash of rice wine vinegar, topped 6 squares of sushi nori with the rice and put into muffin tins. Cut 1/4 pound salmon into small cubes. Added a splash of soy sauce and then some kewpie mayo and sriracha. Tossed the salmon and then filled each cup and baked at 425° for 15 minutes, last two minutes, we turned it to broil. Then added a little more of the spicy mayo and some sesame seeds!! Have you tried this viral food trend? Here’s an idea for a nature inspired Easter table….I love a Monday that starts out with a beach walk that turns into a grabbing handful of birch branches and some lovely moss. I dropped the birch branches into a lobster pot filled with hot water. It softens them so they are easier to work with.

I hammered some thin nails into each log slice and then took the softened branches and wove them back and forth through the nails. I used a paint pen to take the shine off the tips of the nails.

Then I put a little moss into each nest and added a clipping of pussy willows, some little eggs that I bought @shopterrain several years ago and then made tags using the paper bag.

You’ve seen those upside down puff pastry tartlets? We have France on our minds, so we made sort of a Croque Monsieur.

We even made a Béchamel sauce. It was so good, you can’t believe it!

Ingredients:

* Extra Virgin Olive Oil
* 4 Slices French ham, sliced thin
* 8 small slices Gruyère Cheese
* 1 tablespoon Dijon Mustard
* 1 Tablespoon Béchamel Sauce
* 1 sheet puff pastry

How to Assemble:

1. Preheat oven to 350º
2. Line a large baking sheet with parchment
3. Drizzle olive oil in 4 rectangles on the parchment 
4. Top with the ham, Béchamel sauce, mustard, and Gruyère cheese
5. Then place a sheet of puff pastry over the top and press on all four sides. 
6. Pierce with a fork and brush with an egg wash, sprinkle a little flaky sea salt and bake for 15 minutes.
7. Remove from the oven and flip onto a cooling rack. 
8. Serve warm!

Level up your lemon bars with blood oranges. Perfect for Mother’s Day! 
@shopritestores has everything you need to make a blood orange tart that tastes even better than lemon bars!

BLOOD ORANGE TART/BARS
Ingredients for the shortbread crust:
1 cup Bowl & Basket flour
1/4 cup Bowl & Basket sugar
1/2 tsp salt
1/2 cup Bowl & Basket unslated butter 
1/2 tsp vanilla

For the Filling:
1 1/4 cups Bowl & Basket sugar
2 TBSP blood orange zest
1/4 cup Bowl & Basket flour
4 Bowl & Basket eggs
1/2 cup blood orange juice (4-5 blood oranges)
Pinch of salt

After Baking:
1/4 cup freeze dried strawberries
confectioners sugar

Instructions:
-Make the shortbread crust. Use a tart pan with a removable bottom, or 8 x 8 cake pan. Pre-bake the crust, making sure it doesn’t get too brown. 
 -Combine sugar, zest and massage until fragrant. Add flour, eggs, salt, blood orange juice, and vanilla and whisk.
-As soon as crust is out of the oven, strain the blood orange mixture through a mesh strainer into the shortbread crust. 
-Bake until set, about 28-34 minutes. Cool on wire rack for 1 hour, then refrigerate overnight.
-Prepare the pink dust. Blend freeze dried strawberries and sift over the top of the tart or bars. 
-Then dust again with Bowl & Basket confectioners sugar. 

To Serve, Cut slices or bars and arrange on a platter with doilies available in the kitchen supply section at your local ShopRite store….just like mom.

Ina Garten Tomato & Goat Cheese Tarts with Puff Pastry, but let’s make them Upside Down Tomato Goat Cheese Tarts!
🍅Start with one sheet of puff pastry, roll it out and cut 4 rectangles
🍅Slice the onion and sauté with salt and pepper, add a little fresh thyme.
🍅On a baking sheet with parchment paper, make 4 squares on the sheet with olive oil.
🍅Top with a tomato slice, then top it with the sautéed onions.
🍅Add a little herbed goat cheese on top.
Sprinkle with grated parmesan cheese
Place the Puff Pastry on top and using the tines of a fork, go around all 4 edges.
🍅Prick the top of each pastry with the fork.
🍅Brush with an egg wash and sprinkle a little flaky sea Salt.
🍅Bake for about 20 minutes.
🍅Removed from the oven, flip onto a cooling rack.
🍅Start with a new piece of parchment paper. 
🍅Place the tarts that have been turned upside down onto the parchment paper with the tomato that’s now on top.
🍅Place 2-3 shards of parmesan cheese on top of each and place under the broiler for a minute.
🍅Sprinkle a little julienned basil on top (just like Ina) and serve! #inagarten #inagartenrecipe #tomatogoatcheesetart #puffpastry #mostlovelythings #upsidedown #upsidedowntart #explore

Zucchini goat cheese tarts inspired by Ina Garten! But we used the puff pastry upside down method! Recipe below and on the blog! 

* One sheet puff pastry
* 4-ounce of goat cheese (softened a bit)
* One each, zucchini and yellow squash (same size)
* Lemon zest from one lemon
* salt and pepper
* 1/4 cup flour 
* Fresh thyme
* 1 egg for egg wash
* 2 tablespoons olive oil

1. Roll out one sheet of puff pastry, cut six rectangles. Store 2. Keep cold in the refrigerator until ready to use.
2. Slice thin circles of zucchini and yellow squash and allow to drain onto a place for 30 minutes. Then place the rounds on a paper towel and pat dry with an additional towel.
3. Mix the goat cheese with some fresh thyme, lemon zest, salt, and pepper in a small bowl.
4. Prepare a baking sheet lined with parchment paper.
5. Add about 1/2 tablespoon of olive oil in four places, evenly spaced. Layer the zucchini slices in two rows, forming a rectangle over the oil olive oil on the parchment paper.
6. Spread a quarter of the goat cheese mixture on the zucchini and yellow squash slices.
7. Cover with a puff pastry rectangle, pulling it gently to the size you need to cover the filling.
8. Using the tines of a fork, gently go around all four sides with the fork, then prick the inside of each pastry, give each a little egg wash, and sprinkle with sea salt.
9. Pop them into a 350º oven for about 15-17 minutes. When they are golden brown, take them out and flip them over on the baking sheet. Crank the oven to broil and put them back in for a minute or two until golden brown. 
10. Remove from the oven and place on a cooling rack. Once they have cooled slightly, sprinkle with some fresh thyme. The sprinkle of fresh thyme makes the tarts look so beautiful, so please, don’t skip that part!
Enjoy! #goatcheese #goatcheesetart #inagartenrecipe #puffpastry #mostlovelythings #explore

I wanted to make something simple to hang small jars from my new over-the-table rod from @shopterrain 

It takes about 2 minutes to make each sling. 

You’ll need twine and a small jar. Today I’m using them for a few garden flowers, but when I add a votive to the jar, it will need to hang straight. I’ll have a blog post tomorrow. Check stories for information on the crate of twine, the table and the beautiful glassware and linens.

Save this post to remind yourself to save those jars! 

step-by-step instructions:

🌼First, take about 80” of twine. Tie it together in a knot.

🌼Lay it out on the table. I have one big loop and then a smaller loop coming up from the bottom that’s crossing over itself to make an X.

🌼The middle loop needs to be about the same length of the height of the jar you’re using.

🌼Place your jar on top of the X that you made with the middle loop. You can add a piece of tape to help it stay in place. 

🌼Then start by taking the top part of the large loop…like this and put it under the smaller loop. Pull it up and out making a large loop.

🌼Then bring it down over the jar. you should have two inside loops that are close to the jar. Reach inside each smaller loop and grab the outer twine and pull on both sides evenly in an upward direction. 

🌼Adjust the jar making sure the X stays on the bottom of the jar. You also want to try and get the twine close to the grooves or top of your jar to help keep it in place.

🌼This can be added to your over-the-table rod and used with flowers or votives since it’s now even!

Let’s make Paper bag snowflakes but using a combination of Kraft, white and black paper bags. These are fun to make and are great for decorations. I used to use them only at Christmas, but how awesome would these be for a halloween party. 

They cost next to nothing and you could make a dozen in about 30 minutes! SAVE this post to remind yourself to make these at some point from now until Christmas! It’s never too early—IMO!

Here’s what You will need to make one snowflake or star
*8 paper bags
*Hot glue 
*A good pair of scissors (I can’t stress this enough, you have to use the good scissors) 

-Stack the 8 bags (every other color) with the flap facing up
-Draw a “T” down the center of the bag, leaving about an inch from the top
-stack the next bag and secure, repeat until all 8 bags are glued together.
-now you are going to make simple cuts on each side. I make the same on one side as the other. Half circles, triangles, nothing fancy because it’s difficult to cut through 8 bags.
-You can also cut the tips to make it look more like a star.

You might be thinking….why is this necessary? A garlic butter candle? But… it’s the week between Christmas and New Year’s, so I’ll allow it!😉 And here’s how we made it! 

🧈Slice the top off the head of garlic, place in a small roasting pan and drizzle with olive oil. Bake covered.

🧈Add softened butter to a bowl. Mixing in the garlic. Whisk until smooth.

🧈Prepare plastic cups. Make a small hole in the middle of the bottom of the cup. Insert a food-safe wick and fill each cup with half of the butter garlic mixture. 

🧈Make sure the wick is centered. Cover and freeze for at least two hours.

🥖Choose a loaf of bread that’s a least thick enough to hold the butter candle. Make an opening by cutting an X forming a circle for the candle. 

🥖Slice a baguette for serving. Remove the cups from the freezer and cut off the cup. Place into the bread vessel. And allow to come to room temperature!!! Then light and serve! 🧈🕯️

Have you heard of the viral hot chocolate from Glacé on the Upper East side of Manhattan? Hour long lines and customers are raving! It was even in the New York Post yesterday! We decided we needed to make it at home! 

We made the best French hot chocolate using chopped bittersweet chocolate and whole milk. Then we made the meringue that’s going on the rim of the cup, and then of course you’re going to need to toast it! Last, but not least, you’ll need a big dollop of whipped cream. Recipe below in the caption! 

🍫Martha Stewart’s Test Kitchen Favorite Hot Chocolate

For the meringue:
* two egg whites
* 1/4 tsp cream of tartar
Beat on high until stiff peaks form.
* 1/2 cup brown sugar
* 1/4 cup light corn syrup
* 1/4 cup water
* A pinch of cinnamon 
Bring to a boil and stir to dissolve. Add slowly to the egg whites with mixer on low. Increase speed until glossy and stiff. 

Put meringue into a pastry bag and the cut the tip so that you’ll have a wide rim of meringue in the rim of your cup. Then using a  kitchen blow torch, toast the marshmallow rim. Pour in your hot chocolate and add a generous scoop of whipped cream! Enjoy! #worthit @glacenoglu @nypost #hotchocolate #nyc #nycfood #nycfoods #devourpower

January is the perfect time to make ice lanterns! You only need a few cups, plastic containers that are a bit larger than the cups (food storage containers or plastic bowls)— tape the cup to the container or bowl to help keep it in place, fill with water and place outdoors if you live where it’s cold enough, or the freezer will work too. Allow to freeze completely, then run hot water to release the ice lantern and place a candle inside. Take outdoors immediately and enjoy!
